ndo-China -- t13. Imperial Unity Versus Local Autonomy: British Malaya and the Depression of the 1930s -- t14. Crisis and Response: A Study of Foreign Trade and Exchange Rate Policies in Three Southeast Asian Colonies in the 1930s -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe principal cause of the 1930s depression in Southeast Asia lay outside the region — through a sharp contraction in demand for the region’s major commodity exports. But it had important internal causes too: an oversupply of primary commodities and an increasing scarcity of new agricultural land leading to higher rents and lower wages, rising indebtedness and increasing landlessness. This work thoroughly analyses the pre-war depression. It also looks at the changes in the basic structures of the economies of Southeast Asia that were of long-term importance, such as the role of the state in the economy. The authors also draw similarities and contrasts between the 1930s depression and the 1990s Asian crisis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic History.2bisacsh1 aBoomgaard, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoomgaard, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBooth, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrocheux, Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Ian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aClarence-Smith, William Gervase, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoeppers, Daniel F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKratoska, Paul H., 